edu.uidaho.junicon.runtime.junicon.iterators

Interface IIconAtom<T>

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    IconActivation, IconAtom, IconField, IconGlobal, IconIndex, IconRef, IconTmp, IconValue, IconValueArray, IconValueCollection, IconValueGenerator, IconValueJavaIterator, IconValueList, IconValueMap, IconValueNumber, IconValueOther, IconValueSet, IconValueString, IconValueUntyped, IconVar

    public interface IIconAtom<T>
    Interface for reified variables and values. A reified variable, or atom, has a getter and setter like a property, and either holds a reference to an object, or instead can internally just hold the object value. In function terms, a getter is a Supplier.get() or Callable.call(), and a setter is a Consumer.accept(), although here it is presented as set().

    Reified variables are used in Junicon as follows. Class fields are declared as plain values, and in addition have separate reified variables that refer to them, in order to support seamless interoperability with Java. Method parameters, method/block locals, and temporaries are declared as reified variables which just hold the value. Temporaries that appear in the left-hand side of a bound iterator, i.e., (tmp in e), hold an atom rather than a raw value. For external references, we don't declare reified variables, but just construct them in reified form as needed in expressions.

    • Method Detail

      • getEmptyArray

        static Object[] getEmptyArray()
        Get empty array.

      • get

        T get()
        Gets the value of the object referenced by this atom. For temporaries which hold atoms, gets the held atom's value by getTmp().get().

      • set

        void set(T value)
        Sets the object referenced by this atom to the specified value. For temporaries which hold atoms, sets the held atom's value by getTmp().set(v). A value atom is immutable.

      • deref

        T deref()
        Gets the value referenced by this atom. For temporaries which hold atoms, gets the held atom's value by getTmp().set(v). Equivalent to get().

      • setValue

        void setValue(IIconAtom<T> atom)
        Sets the value as an atom, from the given atom's getValue(). 
         Equivalent to: set(atom.get())

      • getValue

        IconValue getValue()
        Gets the value as an atom. Not guaranteed to be typed. Always non-null, may be empty value. 
         Equivalent to: IconValue.create(get())
 Invariant condition: atom.getValue().get() = atom.get()

      • getObject

        Object getObject()
        Gets the value as an object, regardless of type. Equivalent to deref() or get().

      • getAtom

        IIconAtom<T> getAtom()
        Gets the atom held by this temporary. If not temporary, just returns this.

      • setAtom

        void setAtom(IIconAtom<T> atom)
        Sets the atom held by this temporary. If not temporary, does nothing.

      • lastSetFailed

        boolean lastSetFailed()
        Gets if the last set failed. Used by &pos in assignment.

      • onReturn

        IIconAtom<T> onReturn()
        Perform postprocessing on this atom before being returned by an iterators nextAtom(), if filterOnReturn() is set in that iterator. Intended for use by method return and suspend statements. For IconVar, if local then deferences the atom, i.e., gets the value referenced by this atom and promotes it to an atom. For IconIndex and IconField, clones and then freezes the value referenced by this atom. Default is to just return this atom.

      • local

        IIconAtom<T> local()
        Sets if is a method local that is dereferenced on return. Returns this to allow setter chaining.

      • isTemporary

        boolean isTemporary()
        Gets if is a temporary reified atom, which holds another atom.

        For temporaries, deref() is equivalent to getTmp().get().

        In the transforms, deref() is only used for temporaries. An object reference with deref() will be of form: o.deref().x.y | o.deref(). If an object reference ends in deref(), it will be a singular atom that is a temporary. Such an o.deref() without .x.y can only occur inside a primary as an index list, function name, or argument, but never standalone.

      • isActivation

        boolean isActivation()
        Gets if is an atom returned from a continuation, which holds a co-expression to activate.
